       . . . NATIONAL COTTON COUNCIL PILOT CLOSES--BIG ONTYME ACCOUNT . . .
     
     ACS Sales Specialist Diane Biegel and Sales Rep Claire Pribula closed an
     OnTyme application with the National Cotton Council of America for a
     pilot to run 9/86 through 1/87.
     
     The OnTyme pilot will enable the National Cotton Council, located in
     Memphis, Tennessee, to save time and money and to communicate between
     
     - farmers and the USDA
     - its staff members
     - dealers and customers of the cotton industry
     
     GTE Telemail came in with a figure 30% lower than ACS.  But ACS got the
     close due to our superior consulting services, our ability to address
     the National Cotton Council's long-term needs, and the fact that
     Telemail has inferior error checking.
     
     Pribula first called on the National Cotton Council in September '85.
     In May '86, she got the RFP.  She contacted Diane Biegel, and, with the
     help of Nancy Browning, Bill Price, Nancy Shelton, Nick Corsano, and the
     Customer Service Center, made the close in July '86.
     
     According to Nancy Browning, ACS Manager of Business Development, this
     foot in the door has great potential for big future business!
     
     
                  . . . HOW TO PREPARE A WINNING PROPOSAL . . .
     
               by Patt Christie, Sr. Section Mgr., Marketing Media
     
     How well you prepare proposals may determine the success of your
     organization.  Here are some suggested mechanics from a just-announced
     book written to help you market your services:
     
     * Begin each new section at the top of the page
     * Be sure that no section is more than three times the number of pages
       of any other section
     * Place the table of contents and a list of exhibits and appendixes in
       the front of the proposal
     * Try to limit lists to six items; make nine the maximum
     * Include exhibits in the text adjacent to where the exhibit is noted
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
     * Avoid acronyms, abbreviations, and colloquialisms.  Write for an
       uninformed audience that has moderate interest
     * Limit sentence length.  Sentences that run more than 30 words and
       contain more than two ideas are difficult to follow
     * Include a "you will receive" benefit statement for each "we will do"
       statement
     
     Richard  A.   Conner,  Jr.  and  Jeffrey  P.  Davidson,  Marketing  Your
     Consulting and  Professional Services  (New York:  John  Wiley  &  Sons,
     1986[?]).
     
     
